   "source": [
    "# Pandas Series Fundamentals\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook covers the essential concepts of Pandas Series:\n",
    "- Understanding what a Series is\n",
    "- Creating Series from Python lists\n",
    "- Creating Series from NumPy arrays\n",
    "- Working with index and values\n",
    "- Comparing Series with NumPy arrays"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Import required libraries\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import numpy as np"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Understanding Pandas Series\n",
    "\n",
    "A **Series** is a one-dimensional labeled array in Pandas. Think of it as:\n",
    "- A NumPy array with labels (index)\n",
    "- A column in a spreadsheet\n",
    "- A single column from a DataFrame\n",
    "\n",
    "Each value has a corresponding label, making data access more intuitive."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Creating Series from Python Lists"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Example 1: Numeric list with default index\n",
    "temperatures = [72, 68, 75, 80, 77]\n",
    "temp_series = pd.Series(temperatures)\n",
    "print(\"Temperature readings:\")\n",
    "print(temp_series)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Example 2: String list\n",
    "cities = [\"New York\", \"Los Angeles\", \"Chicago\", \"Houston\", \"Phoenix\"]\n",
    "city_series = pd.Series(cities)\n",
    "print(city_series)"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "metadata": {
  "kernelspec": {
   "display_name": "Python 3",
   "language": "python",
   "name": "python3"
  },
  "language_info": {
   "name": "python",
   "version": "3.8.0"
  }
 },
 "nbformat": 4,
 "nbformat_minor": 4
}
,
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Example 3: Custom index\n",
    "scores = [95, 87, 92, 88, 90]\n",
    "score_series = pd.Series(scores, index=[\"Alice\", \"Bob\", \"Charlie\", \"Diana\", \"Eve\"])\n",
    "print(\"Student scores:\")\n",
    "print(score_series)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. Creating Series from NumPy Arrays"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Example 1: Basic NumPy array to Series\n",
    "np_array = np.array([10, 20, 30, 40, 50])\n",
    "np_series = pd.Series(np_array)\n",
    "print(\"Series from NumPy array:\")\n",
    "print(np_series)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Example 2: NumPy array with custom index\n",
    "random_data = np.random.randint(1, 100, size=5)\n",
    "random_series = pd.Series(random_data, index=[\"Mon\", \"Tue\", \"Wed\", \"Thu\", \"Fri\"])\n",
    "print(\"Random values by weekday:\")\n",
    "print(random_series)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Example 3: Data types are preserved\n",
    "float_array = np.array([1.5, 2.7, 3.9, 4.2, 5.8])\n",
    "float_series = pd.Series(float_array)\n",
    "print(\"Float Series:\")\n",
    "print(float_series)\n",
    "print(f\"\\nData type: {float_series.dtype}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Understanding Index and Values\n",
    "\n",
    "Every Series has two main components:\n",
    "- **Values**: The actual data (stored as a NumPy array)\n",
    "- **Index**: The labels for each value"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create a sample Series\n",
    "products = pd.Series(\n",
    "    [29.99, 49.99, 19.99, 99.99, 15.99],\n",
    "    index=[\"Keyboard\", \"Mouse\", \"Cable\", \"Monitor\", \"Mousepad\"]\n",
    ")\n",
    "print(\"Product prices:\")\n",
    "print(products)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Access values\n",
    "print(\"Values:\")\n",
    "print(products.values)\n",
    "print(f\"\\nType: {type(products.values)}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Access index\n",
    "print(\"Index:\")\n",
    "print(products.index)\n",
    "print(f\"\\nType: {type(products.index)}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Positional access (like NumPy)\n",
    "print(\"Positional access:\")\n",
    "print(f\"First item: {products.iloc[0]}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Last item: {products.iloc[-1]}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Label-based access (Pandas advantage!)\n",
    "print(\"Label-based access:\")\n",
    "print(f\"Mouse price: ${products['Mouse']}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Monitor price: ${products['Monitor']}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. Series vs NumPy Arrays\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's compare the key differences:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# NumPy array - no labels\n",
    "np_sales = np.array([100, 150, 200, 175, 225])\n",
    "print(\"NumPy Array:\")\n",
    "print(np_sales)\n",
    "print(f\"\\nAccess by position only: np_sales[0] = {np_sales[0]}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Pandas Series - with labels\n",
    "pd_sales = pd.Series(\n",
    "    [100, 150, 200, 175, 225],\n",
    "    index=[\"Jan\", \"Feb\", \"Mar\", \"Apr\", \"May\"]\n",
    ")\n",
    "print(\"Pandas Series:\")\n",
    "print(pd_sales)\n",
    "print(f\"\\nAccess by position: pd_sales.iloc[0] = {pd_sales.iloc[0]}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Access by label: pd_sales['Jan'] = {pd_sales['Jan']}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Key Differences:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Series have meaningful labels** - Access data by name, not just position\n",
    "2. **Label-based operations** - Operations align by label automatically\n",
    "3. **Built on NumPy** - Series use NumPy arrays internally for performance\n",
    "4. **More intuitive** - Labels make code more readable and maintainable"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. Simple Operations on Series"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create a sample Series\n",
    "numbers = pd.Series([10, 20, 30, 40, 50], index=[\"A\", \"B\", \"C\", \"D\", \"E\"])\n",
    "print(\"Original Series:\")\n",
    "print(numbers)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Mathematical operations\n",
    "print(\"Multiply by 2:\")\n",
    "print(numbers * 2)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\nAdd 5:\")\n",
    "print(numbers + 5)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Statistical operations\n",
    "print(\"Statistical operations:\")\n",
    "print(f\"Mean: {numbers.mean()}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Sum: {numbers.sum()}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Max: {numbers.max()}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Min: {numbers.min()}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Standard deviation: {numbers.std()}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "✓ **Series are 1D labeled arrays** - The foundation of Pandas data structures\n",
    "\n",
    "✓ **Can be created from lists or NumPy arrays** - Flexible data input\n",
    "\n",
    "✓ **Have both index and values** - Labels add meaning to data\n",
    "\n",
    "✓ **Support positional AND label-based access** - Best of both worlds\n",
    "\n",
    "✓ **Built on NumPy** - Fast and efficient operations\n",
    "\n",
    "### Next Steps:\n",
    "- Practice creating Series with different data types\n",
    "- Experiment with custom indexes\n",
    "- Move on to DataFrames (2D labeled data)"
   ]
  }
 ]
}
